# UniPilot Database (MongoDB)

All persistent data MUST be stored in MongoDB.

## Persistence
- Store all persistent application data (users, jobs, AI results, student records) in MongoDB.
- Persist MongoDB data on a named Docker volume so it survives container restarts.
- Do not use in-memory or file storage as the source of truth for persistent data.

## Network Exposure (strict)
- MongoDB is internal only — never publish its port to the host.
- Only backend containers (API, worker, AI) on the private Docker network may connect.
- Load the Mongo connection URI from an environment variable; never hardcode credentials.

## Data Modeling & Validation
- Define explicit schemas/models for every collection.
- Validate documents at the application boundary before writing (see security rule).
- Enforce uniqueness where needed (e.g. unique index on user email).
- Add indexes for frequently queried fields (user id, job status) for performance.

## Safe Data Handling
- NEVER store passwords in plain text. Persist only bcrypt hashes.
- Never store secrets or raw provider keys in the database.
- Use the repository pattern: business logic depends on a repository interface, not the driver directly.
- Follow immutable update patterns — build new documents/updates rather than mutating shared state.

## Ownership & Access
- Every student-owned document records its owner (user id).
- Repository queries for student data must scope by the authenticated user id to prevent cross-account access.

## Reliability
- The app must wait for / retry the MongoDB connection on startup (works with Docker healthchecks).
- Handle DB errors explicitly; never silently swallow write/read failures.
